      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "120dce9c0a08a218",
      "text": "However, our attention is drawn to these four categories in particular because they address very fundamental socio-technological aspects of digitization and, moreover, connect to foci of memory research introduced long before digitization: storage as a precondition of media-mediated memory and archiving (Assmann 2001; Garde-Hansen et al. 2009; Moss 2017). Datafication as a socio-technological extension of analog textual and (audio-)visual objectification of memories and their canonization (Erll and Nünning 2004; Assmann 2008; Esposito 2016). Technological as well as social networking as a precondition for the medial dissemination of memories and the emergence of collective memories (Assmann 1988; Baer 2001; Erll and Nünning 2004; Zierold 2006). And last but not least, affectivity as one of the distinguishing features between history as an analytical-critical examination of the past and remembering as a living, group-related, and thus also affective construction of the past by communities of rememberers (Halbwachs 1991 [1952]; Nora 1989; Wang 2008)."
    },
