      "id": "20d94600973b658f",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "20d94600973b658f",
        "text": "One example is the discussion about the \"right to be forgotten\", which found its way into the EU General Data Protection Regulation in 2018 as the \"right to erasure\" and ensures the enforcement of deletions of personal data. This right stems from a judgment requiring Google to delete links to websites containing personal data under certain circumstances (Singer and Beck 2019). However, the underlying fundamental problem of forgetting under conditions of the digital engages memory research even beyond this specific legal issue (Ghezzi et al. 2014; Tirosh 2017). Another example is the Facebook Memories feature (Migowski and Fernandes Araújo 2019; Humphreys 2020), which, according to Facebook's help section, cannot be disabled but \"[d]u can specify what you see under Memories by hiding people or data you do not want to be remembered\" (Meta 2022)."
