        "text": "In view of the further development of such algorithms and artificial intelligence on various platforms, it does not seem to be a central problem to prioritize the past for remembering, to select it, and to make it findable in the growing cosmos of digital lenses. Looking back at the invention of printing in the early modern era, Esposito (2016, 335) notes that new technologies have always required the development of new retrieval systems, such as indexing in libraries and archives, which, based on corresponding databases, made it possible to locate specific knowledge - and thus also the past - without having to be able to remember the contents in advance. As is the case with search engines today, it was sufficient to know, on the basis of the data on the holdings, which category or keywords had to be searched for. Datafication is therefore not new per se and can be found historically even in pre-digital times (Koenen et al. 2021). Thanks to these systems, the concern about the uncontrollability of the past on the Internet is therefore also considered by Esposito to be rather unfounded: […]"
